Container introduction

Roman Pahl

2021-09-27

Source: vignettes/Container.Rmd
Container.Rmd

Introduction

While the Container class is ready to be used by itself, usually one will want to work with objects created from one of it’s derived classes Deque, Set, or Dict. Nevertheless, since all Container methods are inherited to these classes, this vignette still provides useful examples for all general container methods.

In principle, the Container class provides two interfaces to work with Container objects:

  • R6 interface
  • S3 interface

Both interfaces provide the same functionality with some added operators for the S3 interface. As such, it’s a matter of taste which interface to use and both are covered in the respective sections R6 objects and methods and S3 methods below.

R6 objects and methods

library(container)
#> 
#> Attaching package: 'container'
#> The following object is masked from 'package:stats':
#> 
#>     update
#> The following object is masked from 'package:base':
#> 
#>     replace
#devtools::load_all()

A table of all methods is found in the overview vignette.

Initialization

co <- Container$new()
data.class(co)
#> [1] "Container"
co$is_empty()
#> [1] TRUE

Add elements

By default, elements internally are stored in a list and therefore can be of any type.

co$add(1)
#> [1]
co$add("A")
#> [1, "A"]
co$add(data.frame(B=1, C=2))
#> [1, "A", <<data.frame(1x2)>>]

The internal representation can always be retrieved directly using the values function.

co$values()
#> [[1]]
#> [1] 1
#> 
#> [[2]]
#> [1] "A"
#> 
#> [[3]]
#>   B C
#> 1 1 2

The container’s print method presents the content more compact similar to utils::str

co$print()
#> [1, "A", <<data.frame(1x2)>>]

If initialized with an R object, the type of the object is adopted to allow for efficient internal representations, if required.

ints <- Container$new(integer())

The add method supports chaining.

ints$add(1)$add(2)$add(3.7)
#> [integer(), 1, 2, 3.7]
ints
#> [integer(), 1, 2, 3.7]

Initialization also works with vectors.

(ints <- as.container(1:10))
#> [1L, 2L, 3L, 4L, 5L, 6L, 7L, 8L, 9L, 10L]

Delete elements

ints$has(11)
#> [1] FALSE
ints$has(7)
#> [1] TRUE
ints$discard(7)$has(7)
#> [1] FALSE
(ints$delete(8))
#> [1L, 2L, 3L, 4L, 5L, 6L, 9L, 10L]

Using delete on non-existent elements throws an error,

ints$delete(8)
#> Error: 8 is not in Container

but discard does not.

ints$discard(8) # ok
#> [1L, 2L, 3L, 4L, 5L, 6L, 9L, 10L]

S3 methods

The S3 methods are very similar to the object oriented R6 methods presented above. The above examples are repeated.

Initialization

co <- container()
is_empty(co)
#> [1] TRUE

Since the created objects are still the same as when created via the R6 interface, they always work both ways:

co$is_empty()
#> [1] TRUE

Add elements

By default, elements internally are stored in a list and therefore can be of any type.

add(co, 1)
#> [1]
add(co, "A")
#> ["A"]
add(co, data.frame(B=1, C=2))
#> [<<data.frame(1x2)>>]

The internal representation can always be retrieved directly using the as.list function.

as.list(co)
#> list()

Initialization also works with vectors.

ints <- as.container(1:10)

Iterator

For a description of the available Iterator methods please refer to the online help.

?Iterator

An iterator is created from a Container object as follows:

members <- Container$new(c("Lisa", "Bob", "Joe"))

it <- members$iter()
it
#> <Iterator> at position 0 / 1

The has_next and get_next methods can be used to iterate through the container’s elements.

while(it$has_next()) {
    it$next_iter()
    print(it)
    print(it$get_value())
}
#> <Iterator> at position 1 / 1 
#> [[1]]
#> [1] "Lisa" "Bob"  "Joe"

Once iterated to the last element, trying to iterate further leads to an error.

it$next_iter()
#> Error in it$next_iter(): Iterator has no more elements.
it$has_next()
#> [1] FALSE

To reset the iterator, call begin

it$begin()
it
#> <Iterator> at position 1 / 1

The calls to next and get can be combined in one command:

while(it$has_next()) {
    print(it$get_next())
}

There is a S3 interface for the Iterator class as well.

begin(it)

is.iterator(it)
#> [1] TRUE
pos(it)
#> [1] 1
while(has_next(it)) {
    next_iter(it)
    print(get_value(it))
}

pos(it)
#> [1] 1
has_next(it)
#> [1] FALSE
